segments.text: Tuesday, February 12, testing, testing, one, two, three.
Testing some more, testing some more on the 12th of February, testing.
Testing a second time, testing a second time on February 12.
W.D.
Schultz.
This is February 12, and we're in the heart of the Evans Library now.
In fact, inside what once was the Engineering Library.
I have the honor and pleasure of recording the memories of W.D.
Scotes, that's S-C-O-A-T-E-S, Bill Scotes to his many friends.

Mr. Scotes, to introduce you and your family to anybody that will hear this tape or read the transcription, describe your family, when they got here, where, what was their background before they came to College Station.
Where did your mom and dad grow up and where did your dad go to school?
Well, what we call the Scotes, the United States Scotes family came
was brought to Milwaukee, Wisconsin by his—by a cousin of
The Scopes family was brought to Milwaukee by a 50-ton boat from Ramsgate, England across the Atlantic
to the St. Lawrence River, down the St. Lawrence River, to the canal up in the lakes, and to Milwaukee.
He brought the entire family of Richard William Scotes, who was born in 1818.
And they were
Englishman from Ramsgate, England, which is on the mouth of the Thames River.
And they were brought here by Francis, Samuel Francis Coates, who was a seaman, had that 50-ton boat.
They also brought the family of
Sophie, which was William Scote's wife, and they, that family, that man was a tailor, and they lived right downtown in what is now Milwaukee.
And your dad was born when?
He was born in
This is all the family they brought.
See, another thing on this thing here.
This line number
It starts off with an S for Scotes.
Then it'll turn to a numeral.
And then it'll turn back to a letter.
Because the Scotes family, Richard, he had a Richard William and a William Richard and a William Richard and so on down the line.
But your dad grew up in Milwaukee?
No, he grew up in Crown Point.
Where?
Crown Point, Indiana.
How do you spell Crown Point?
Crown Point.
Oh, Crown Point.
Crown Point.
Yes, Crown Point.
And what did his father do for a living?
He was a witcher.
And then...
He was one...
He was...
His father was named William Richard Schoes.
He was born on December the 17th,
1852, in Ramsgate, England.
So that's your grandfather?
That, yeah, that's my grandfather.
No, my great-grandfather.
Oh.
Yeah, it's dad's father.
Oh, yeah.
And they, they were at Richard William.
How big was Crown, was Crown Point?
It was a pretty good-sized town.
It was, it's about 50 miles south of the end of Lake Michigan.
It's right up there.
Up in northern Indiana.
Yeah, northwestern Indiana.
And your dad went to public school there?
Well, he married Emmeline Townsend Coffin.
No, he, yeah.
Is that your dad or your grandfather?
That's my dad.
Your dad.
No, no, that's, that's his, that's his father.
Okay.
William Richard Scotes.
His father married an Emmeline Townsend Coughlin.
We called her grandmother.
That's the way we knew her.
And she was married to a Coughlin, Scotes.
She was married later to a
Charles W. King in 1889 and later was married to a Thomas Kearney, 1892.
But, and she lost one boy, the oldest boy, Harry, who died of
gangrene.
Stuck a pair of scissors in his leg.
So your dad went to school there in Crown Point?
Only to the fourth grade.
And then he traveled with
The Tierneys were in New Hampshire, Concord, New Hampshire.
That's your father with the Tierneys?
Yeah, my grandmother married a Tierney, so there's a half-brother.
call him Harry William Scotes.
He had his name changed from Tierney to Scotes.
And so they, they landed, they moved out of Milwaukee to a little town called Oak
Creek, which is in the south, south part of, uh, Milwaukee County.
And through the years there was always a, a clan of somebody that was skinned to us in that town.
And that's where, uh, well, wait a minute.
The reason the Scots had gotten mixed up in it was that, um,
Grandmother Schultz was a very opinionated woman and took care of a lot of people.
Matter of fact, she was the first woman that ever had a, what do you call it, an expensive drug pharmacist?
She was the first woman that ever had a father in the state of Illinois, Indiana.
And she had a younger sister that was, she had a younger sister that was very sickly.
and she would come up from Crown Point to this little town of Goat Creek and to tend to her sister and that's where she married, that's where she met the Scotes family.
So that's the joining of the
The Coffin and the Scotes family was through that.
They lived there about a year, and then they all moved back to Clown Point.
But my father never, Daniel Scotes never went beyond the fourth grade.
And then what did he do for a living, your dad?

well he was a kid and i don't know what he did there for a living uh oh he had to attend the grandmother had married this uh dr charles king and he was a doctor and dad had to take care of the horses and the carriages for him
So they finally moved to New Hampshire.
What was the big town?
Manchester.
They finally moved up there.
And then Thomas Tierney left them.
In 1900, he left my grandmother and her children.
I see there's Daniel, there's Richard, and Bessie, and Harry.
Four of them.
Left them destitute in Manchester.
I mean destitute.
And so a woman, Townsend,
See, Grandmother was related to the Coffins and the Townsends out of Maine, and one of them came, she was living in Boston, and she arranged one to move down to what they called South Boston.
Okay.
In the, and was, and that's where the
stayed for a while and in 1900 uh grandmother farmed her children out to her uh her family she was a she was a coffin one of
So who did your dad get farmed out to?
Her brother.
He had a farm at Scott City, Kansas.
He was sent there.
Where is Scott City?
It's in the western half of it.
They raised horses.
Way out on the prairie.
And Joe, your dad would have been about what age then?
Seventeen.
Okay.

and so they he was out there in 1900 and they raised those horses out there apparently most all sizes I mean all breeds all breeds of horses they had some Clydesdales out there they had the Morgans out there and daddy daddy had to take them
on the train back to Connecticut where they sold them.
He rode the train with the horses.
And that's what, and people don't realize it now, that's what the caboose was for.
Did you know that?
Caboose was to- To haul animals?
No, to haul people that cared for them.
Oh, oh, oh, on a freight train.
On a freight train.
Caboose, we used to have them.
function of that was to haul the people that were on the train that had something to do like carrying for horses or carrying for ice and vegetables or fowl.
They shipped a lot of fowl in those days.
were shipped out of western Kansas.
One of my uncles told me that he killed 470 of those ducks at one time.
And shipped them to Kansas City.
And how long did your dad do that, work on the farm?
I don't know a great deal about what was there, other than that, what I told you.
But someone had helped him with his schooling.
At that point in time, I understood it was some school in Davenport, Iowa.
I don't have any other recollection of that.
The next thing Dad did was he went to Ames, Iowa, and
He passed the entrance examinations in 1906.
To go to Iowa State.
Now, there's a gap there, see?
I really don't know a whole lot about it.
He wasn't very, very close with his mouth about that.
But then he went to Ames.
He went three years as a civil engineer.
from 1906 to 1909, and in 1909 they offered, they brought, they brought Mr. Dr. Davison from the University of Nebraska to Ames and formed the Ag Engineering Department, and they gave
they asked him, they asked dad if he wanted to change to ag engineering, he'd take this special course that they had and he'd get a degree in ag engineering, which he did.
So he was more like a civil than he was, but he, he, of course he had the experience of being on that farm out there, because that was a rough time out there then, even then.
Did he ever say what he was hoping to be professionally when he got out of college?
No, no.
He just took off and made his own.
And then he was offered a position as head of the Ag Engineering Department at Mississippi State in 1910.
And my mother, who is... Where did they meet?
She was in Iowa State also.
Oh, okay.
She went three years.
In 1910, she stayed out.
And Ms. Mary Eleanor Lamb...
She was raised right out of Illinois, which is halfway between Rockford and Freeport in the northern part of Illinois, on a farm.
She was raised on a farm, a big farm.
And so they married, and she went to... At Thanksgiving time, she went down to...
St. Louis, and he went up to St. Louis, and they got married.
And so then he started his professional degree, his professional from then on.
Over at Mississippi State?
Yeah.
And as the war came on, Mississippi State, and also A&M right here, we had to train
kids to drive trucks, take care of trucks.
Was that part of his duty?
That was part of his duty.
And they trained over there.
And he got his half-brother, Harry.
My grandmother couldn't control his half-brother.
And so he sent him to Dan Scotes and Albert Lamb at the University of Mississippi.
Mississippi State.
Mississippi State.
What's the name of that town?
Starkville.
Starkville.
And he turned, Harry turned into a good mechanic.
And he was the one that helped Dan with the training of all those soldiers.
But what happened was that the governor of Mississippi would take it upon himself
when some man would make something he didn't like, and they'd go up there and fire him.
And Dad didn't like that political end of it.
And so he was offered the job here at A&M.
Do you have any idea what pay he got when he came?
1900 for 12 months?
there was something about that.

So he evidently knew that quite a while because he went to, when we were, we normally went to Mother's Place in Illinois during the summertime and they had some time off and we'd normally go up there and
In 1919, he went to the factory for a Huffmobile and bought a big sedan.
Not a sedan, no, a touring car.
A big touring car.
That was a fancy car.
Yeah, yeah.
A great big devil.
So when we—when they—
He finished his duties at Starkville, and we all boarded that car.
Not only did we bring—we had five of us, you know.
We had Dad, Mama, and three children.
We had another family, Martin, that had a man, his wife, and a little boy.
Were all of you in the Hupmobile?
We were all in the Hupmobile.
And you drove it from Starkville?
We drove it from Starkville, and we got to Baton Rouge.
And we started across, that day we started across west out of Baton Rouge.
And about late in the afternoon,
And the roads were getting awful terrible, just plumb terrible.
And so he, lo and behold, on the north side of the road, this plantation appeared, just like the movies have it.
There was a road going up there, and there were trees on both sides, and a big old house sitting back in the back end of it.
That's what it looked like.
And so we stopped, and we drove up in there, and he said we could go ask about the road ahead and so forth.
And the lady greeted him and said, you're not going anywhere.
You're staying here tonight.
like a bed and breakfast, they put all of us up in that big old house.
And we stayed there.
And the next day, we drove back to Baton Rouge.
And then we had to stay in Baton Rouge one day, because Dad had to make arrangements to ship that car to Houston.
There were no transport across that.
No bridge across the river.
No, just no road at all.
And that storm, I think it's the storm of 1919 out of Corpus, hurt him and put enough water in there.
Because when we boarded that train, we were up there, and I can see it yet.
That's just a continuous storm.
built up with none but railroad tracks on it all the way down, just as far as you could see.
Now you were five years, this 1919?
Six years old.
Well I just went on and on.
And so we got to Houston and then we got some train tickets and came on up here.
So the car was shipped all the way here?
No, it was shipped to Houston.
To Houston, okay.
And later we went.
Oh, later you got it.
Later we obtained it.
It wasn't a special trip down there to obtain it.
And the road between here and Houston wasn't anything to take.
As a matter of fact, there were only three pieces of pavement in this county.
Really?
Where were they?
Well, if you want, there was
north of Main Street and Bryan was paved.
There was a road from, from Bryan to the college, paved, just like it is.
Was it Old College Road?
Old College Road.
And you'd come up there and get next to the railroad and go down there to Boyd's Corner.
That was called Boyd's Corner, and then you went back up to Northgate, and you could enter the college.
One went straight on.
It never existed.
Where was the third one, the third pavement?
It was in a mile of track, a mile of concrete across the bow.
It was right there where you get ready to cross the Navasota.
Oh, oh, oh.

down south yeah when you went in you came off the came off this and you went down into the bog because now the old highway is on the west side was the west side following the railroad yeah uh almost to navasota well yeah yeah
Yeah, you had to cross there right there before you got to the river.
There was a bridge on the river, but it was on the east side.
So you had to crawl up over the top of the tracks and cross the track and keep on going.
You went to Navasota, you didn't go to the new route.
So that's where that came in.
And there were three paces of pavement, and that was it.
All right, describe...
the campus as you earliest remember it.
What was it like when you... Well, it was just a square piece of property like this.
You had, you came into it at Boyd's Corner, which is a, which is an underpass now.
Mm-hmm.
Boyette's.
Mm-hmm.
That's the University Drive.
Mm-hmm.
Yeah.
Used to have to climb all the crime.
You had to climb
On that railroad, you'd have to climb 20, 25 feet up an incline to go over the railroad.
So it was hard to drive a wagon across it?
Hard to drive anything.
But it was there.
And so that road was a gravel road.
There were no pavements, I remember.
It went to the corner on where Texas is now.
That was gravel.
There was a gravel road that went down Texas to the Shiloh.
That was a fraternal club and a church.
And they had a cemetery, which is now called the State Cemetery.
Was there a road on the south side of the campus?
No.
Where Jersey Street used to be?
No, there were not.
And east of what is now Texas Avenue was just open land, wasn't it?
It was just open land.
There was no road there, except for this one gravel road down the property line on the east side of it.
That was the only place there was to go.
All right, and what buildings were there on the campus that were most noticeable?
Main building.
All of the, the entire thing faced the railroad.
So the academic building was here at that time.
With a door.
From there west, it was just about.
